<div class="bl">

  <p>But mullein only handles one half of the equation&nbsp;—&nbsp;the clearance side. I needed something for the protection side. That’s where <strong>chlorophyll</strong> comes in.</p>

  <p>Chlorophyll&nbsp;—&nbsp;the compound that makes plants green&nbsp;—&nbsp;is one of nature’s most concentrated antioxidants. While mullein works on clearing mucus and calming airway irritation, chlorophyll tackles the oxidative stress that continues wearing on respiratory tissue long after exposure stops. Think of oxidative stress as a fire that’s still smoldering in your cells&nbsp;—&nbsp;even after you’ve removed the fuel. <strong>Chlorophyll helps put out the embers.</strong></p>

  <p>Here’s something most people don’t know: chlorophyll and hemoglobin&nbsp;—&nbsp;the molecule in your blood that carries oxygen&nbsp;—&nbsp;are almost structurally identical. The difference comes down to a single atom at the center: magnesium in chlorophyll, iron in hemoglobin. Everything else is nearly the same. Scientists have studied this relationship for decades, and many researchers believe this molecular similarity is part of why chlorophyll is so readily accepted by the body&nbsp;—&nbsp;and why it appears to be particularly beneficial to the lungs and respiratory system.</p>

