<div class="bl">

  <h2>The Questions You Should Be Asking</h2>

  <p><strong>“If this works, why hasn’t my doctor brought it up?”</strong></p>

  <p>Because there’s no pharmaceutical company funding a $50 million trial on a plant that grows wild in ditches across America. Mullein can’t be patented. Neither can chlorophyll. That means no one profits from proving they work&nbsp;—&nbsp;which means the research gets funded slowly and in small batches. Your doctor isn’t hiding anything. The system just doesn’t have a financial incentive to hand them the data. That’s a funding problem, not an efficacy problem. (That’s also why we funded our own clinical trial&nbsp;—&nbsp;because no one else was going to.)</p>

  <p><strong>“I’ve tried supplements before. They did nothing.”</strong></p>

  <p>Which ones? Most “lung health”&nbsp;supplements are repackaged multivitamins with a leaf on the label. They throw in vitamin C, some zinc, maybe a sprinkle of NAC&nbsp;—&nbsp;ingredients studied for immune function, not respiratory clearance. If you tried a product that didn’t target both clearance <em>and</em> antioxidant protection, you didn’t try this protocol. You tried something that happens to come in the same bottle shape. And those products didn’t put themselves through a triple-blind, placebo-controlled trial. This one did.</p>

  <p><strong>“Can it really make a difference after this many years of exposure?”</strong></p>

  <p>Here’s what the research says about your body’s capacity. A landmark 2020 study published in <em>Nature</em> (Yoshida et al., Vol. 578, pp. 266–272) found that <strong>ex-smokers had four times more genetically healthy cells in their airways than current smokers&nbsp;—&nbsp;representing up to 4 in 10 of their total airway cells.</strong> These cells showed minimal damage from tobacco-specific mutation processes. The takeaway: your body retains more capacity than most people assume, even after decades of exposure. The question isn’t whether that capacity exists&nbsp;—&nbsp;it’s whether you’re doing anything to support it.</p>

